<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<html xmlns:MadCap="http://www.madcapsoftware.com/Schemas/MadCap.xsd" MadCap:fileTags="Tags/okta-authors.Robert Milkovich">
    <body>
        <li>In step 6 of <MadCap:xref href="../policies/add-okta-sign-on-policy-rule.htm">Add a [%=okta-feature-names.Okta sign-on policy%] rule</MadCap:xref>, configure the following conditions as specified:<ul><li><code>AND</code>&#160;<span class="uicontrol">Primary factor is</span>: Select <span class="uicontrol">Password / IDP / any factor allowed by app sign on rules</span>. This allows <MadCap:variable name="okta-feature-names.Okta FastPass" /> users to have passwordless authentication.</li><div class="noteOkta"><p class="noteContent"><span class="wintitle">Important:</span> Changing the default configuration <span class="uicontrol">to Password / IDP / any factor allowed by app sign on rules</span> will affect all of your protected apps. It removes the global password requirement from the <MadCap:variable name="okta-feature-names.Okta sign-on policy" /> and transfers responsibility for defining and enforcing authentication criteria to each of your app sign-on policies. Before you change this configuration, create  strong  app sign-on policies for all of your apps. If you don't do this for all of your apps, users could be able to access apps with any single enrolled factor.</p></div><li><code>AND</code>&#160;<span class="uicontrol">Secondary factor is</span>: Clear the <span class="uicontrol">Require secondary factor</span> checkbox. This allows <MadCap:variable name="okta-feature-names.Okta FastPass" /> users to sign in  without using biometrics.	</li></ul></li>
    </body>
</html>